Of course. This is a significant UI consolidation and enhancement story. The goal is to modernize a key view by replacing an old data source with two new, more relevant ones, and providing clear summary counts.
Here is a complete Jira user story to capture this requirement.
Jira User Story
Title: Assessable Unit View: Display EIM Issues & Exceptions, Hide Legacy Findings
User Story:
As an assessor or risk manager viewing an assessable unit, I want to see a clear summary of all associated "Enterprise Issue Management" (EIM) issues and "Non-Issue Exceptions," including counts of open and closed items, and I want the outdated "Issues and Findings" section to be hidden, so that I have a complete, accurate, and uncluttered view of all relevant issues in one place.
Problem Statement:
The current assessable unit view is incomplete and misleading. It prominently displays the legacy "Issues and Findings" section, which is being phased out, while failing to show two new, critical sources of information: "Enterprise Issue Management" issues and "Non-Issue Exceptions."
This forces users to navigate to multiple, separate modules to get a full picture of an assessable unit's risk posture, creating inefficiency and a high probability that critical issues or exceptions will be missed during an assessment. To make informed decisions, users need a single, consolidated view that displays all current and relevant issue types while hiding the obsolete ones.
Acceptance Criteria (Checklist Style):
1. Enterprise Issue Management (EIM) Display:
 * A new section titled "Enterprise Issue Management" must be visible on the assessable unit view.
 * This section must display a list of all EIM issues associated with the assessable unit.
 * A summary count of all Open EIM issues must be clearly visible.
 * A summary count of all Closed EIM issues must be clearly visible.
 * The definition of "Open" and "Closed" statuses must align with the EIM module's status definitions.
2. Non-Issue Exceptions Display:
 * A new section titled "Non-Issue Exceptions" must be visible on the assessable unit view.
 * This section must display a list of all Non-Issue Exceptions associated with the assessable unit.
 * A summary count of all Open exceptions must be clearly visible.
 * A summary count of all Closed exceptions must be clearly visible.
3. Hiding Legacy Section:
 * The entire section related to the old "Issues and Findings" must be completely removed from the assessable unit view.
4. General & UI/UX:
 * The new "Enterprise Issue Management" and "Non-Issue Exceptions" sections should be clearly distinct from each other.
 * If there are zero issues or exceptions of a certain type, the counts should display "0" rather than hiding the section.
 * The page layout should remain clean and organized after these changes.
 * The performance of the assessable unit page should not be negatively impacted by loading these new sections.
Why this User Story is Effective:
 * Holistic Title: The title summarizes all three parts of the request (Add EIM, Add Exceptions, Hide Legacy).
 * Clear Business Value: The problem statement focuses on the negative business impact of the current design (inefficiency, risk of missing information) and the positive outcome of the change (a single, consolidated view).
 * Grouped Criteria: The acceptance criteria are broken down into logical sub-sections, making it easy for developers and testers to address each part of the request systematically.
 * Specificity on Counts: It explicitly calls for separate "Open" and "Closed" counts, which is a key part of your request and crucial for at-a-glance understanding.
 * Considers the Edge Case: The criterion to display "0" instead of hiding sections ensures a consistent user experience, regardless of the data.
